        "description": "{\"blocks\":[{\"key\":\"1vrgi\",\"text\":\"Chapter 2 from the book Behave by the neuroscientist Robert Sapolski explains the role of the amygdala region in the brain. It is the place that, the way I understand it, deals with the uncertain and with survival: with aggression, anxiety, fear and sexual motivation. \",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[{\"offset\":24,\"length\":6,\"style\":\"ITALIC\"}],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"30fu5\",\"text\":\"I find this particularly intriguing. Why is sexual motivation in the same group as the other 3? The book says that aggression and sex are alike, as the body is practicaly doing the same thing (the heart rate, for example, is the same). We kill and have sex because of the uncertainty the future holds. \\\"The person next to me has a gun, if I kill him first maybe I can avoid dying an thus my genes survive\\\" and \\\"this man or woman looks nice, maybe we can have children and thus my genes survive\\\"\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"ag3so\",\"text\":\"This leads to many questions. Why is one frowned upon, while the other one is cherished? should both be on the same level of social acceptance? Is one wrong and the other right? why do we share this behavior with animals?\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}}],\"entityMap\":{}}",
