        "domain": "TLHw7WBelVuIdJoNHEGF",
        "fileName": "",
        "description": "White dwarfs are formed after the death of a massive star, but that are not massive enough to collapse into a black hole. They are very dense, as their volume is similar to that of planet earth and its mass is similar to that of our sun (too much mass is encapsulated in such a little space). This creates a huge gravitational pull on its core, much more stronger than its hydrostatic force (which should counter that gravitational force so that it doesn't collapse). However, these dying stars are composed mostly of electrons, and these particles (categorized as fermions) follow a statistical property which states that they dislike being close to each other. They 'resist' being brought together, and this is what counters the huge gravitational force. This statistical property of electrons is the reason for white dwarfs existence."
