        "title": "The importance of vitamin C from the sun: part 1",
        "domain": "zIvNmah8LhNAGOHRn1df",
        "isDescriptionRaw": 0,
        "fileName": "",
        "description": "Most people don't get enough vitamin D in their daily life; a unique vitamin with necessary overall benefits for the body. Low levels of it have been linked to osteoporosis, cancer, depression and muscle weakness. It’s important to know that the sun’s UVB rays, which when in contact with the skin provide the energy for vitamin D synthesis to occur, cannot enter through windows, so people who work next to sunny windows are still prone to vitamin D deficiency. The right way of getting all your necessary vitamin D in is: first, exposing around a third of your skin to the sun; wearing a tank top and shorts for 10–30 minutes (without sunscreen) three times per week during the summer should be enough for most people with lighter skin. People with darker skin may need a little bit longer. Second, it is recommended to expose at noon because the sun is at its highest point, and its UVB rays are most intense, plus many studies also show that the body is most efficient at making vitamin D at noon and you would need to expose for less time.",
