        "description": "Our sun is composed mostly of hydrogen atoms, and they constantly fuse to create helium. In this reaction, 4 hydrogen atoms produce 1 helium. However, the mass of these 4 atoms combined is slightly more than that of a single helium. This change in mass produces a change in energy, according to Einstein's famous formula ( E = m*c^2 ). Now imagine the number of times this happens in our sun, as it is approximately 70% hydrogen and its size is gargatuan ( 1,300,000 earths would fit inside it). These reactions produce energy in the form of radiation, and this is the reason our sun shines.",
